Single File Programming Question
Find the Correct Shelf Position

A warehouse manager in Coimbatore maintains a sorted list of product codes in ascending order. When a new product code arrives, the manager must determine:

whether the code already exists in the list
if it does not exist, the exact index where it should be inserted to keep the list sorted
Instead of printing only one number, the system should print richer information:

the insertion index

the status:

Present if the target already exists
Insert if the target is not present and must be inserted
Input format :
The first line contains an integer n — the size of the sorted array
The second line contains n space-separated integers in ascending order
The third line contains an integer target
Output format :
First line: print the insertion index as Position: index
Second line: print the status as Status: Present or Status: Insert

Code constraints :
1 <= n <= 10^4
-10^4 <= nums[i] <= 10^4
nums contains distinct values in ascending order
-10^4 <= target <= 10^4
Expected approach: O(log n) using binary search.

Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
4
1 3 5 6
5
Output 1 :
Position: 2
Status: Present
Input 2 :
4
1 3 5 6
2
Output 2 :
Position: 1

Solution:

// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
   int n;
   cin >> n;
   
   vector<int> arr(n);
   
   for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
       cin >> arr[i];
   }
   
   int k;
   cin >> k;
   
   int l = 0;
   int r = n - 1;
   
   while(l <= r){
       
       int mid = l + (r - l) / 2;
       
       if(arr[mid] == k){
           cout << "Position: " << mid << endl;
           cout << "Status: Present";
           return 0;
       }
       else if(arr[mid] < k){
           l = mid + 1;
       }
       else{
           r = mid - 1;
       }
   }
   
   // Target not found
   cout << "Position: " << l << endl;
   cout << "Status: Insert";
   
   return 0;
}
